Black's king already on the kingside we can follow suit, although there's
nothing wrong with a 7.d3 Nc6 8.O-O move order should you prefer.} Nc6 {
This natural development is unsurprisingly almost always seen. It's by no
means impossible that a club opponent would want to go for a double fianchetto.
We can dream about 7...b6?? 8.e5 , which would already be game over.} 8. d3 {
Our standard development. Even if you are happy with a Maroczy position,
please don't fall for 8.d4 ? cxd4 9.Nxd4 Nxe4 ! 10.Nxc6 Nxc3 when Black is
already somewhat for choice.} Rb8 {Black decides to prepare ...b5.} 9. h3 {
Once again, a useful prophylactic device to side-step 9.Be3 a6.} a6 {Black's
main move, trying to force through ...b5.} 10. a4 {White doesn't want to allow
Black easy counterplay, so clamps down on ...b5.} Ne8 {Black's most common
move, again rerouting the Knight to c7. Once again, he has also tried a great
number of alternatives, so we'll focus on the most important and instructive
examples:} 11. Be3 Nc7 {Black's main move by some margin, although it may not
be best.} 12. d4 {And why not?} cxd4 13. Nxd4 Ne6 {Black's main move by some
margin, continuing to fight for control of d4.} 14. Nde2 {Keeping pieces on
and so Black a bit cramped.} Nc5 15. Rb1 {We also like this move, stepping off
the long diagonal, menacing b4 and provoking Black's next.} Nb4 16. b3 Bd7 17.
Nd5 {Favourably transforming the structure. 17.Qd2 b6 18.Bd4 is also a
pleasant edge for White should you prefer to angle for an f4 and Kingside
attack plan.} Nxd5 18. exd5 {The right way to recapture, and not 18.cxd5 ? b5
when Black breaks free.} Qc8 19. Kh2 {This entails an exchange sacrifice, but
we prefer it to 19.g4 f5 20.f3 , as White is going to obtain a fair amount of
compensation.} Bf5 {Seemingly spelling trouble for the white Rook...} 20. Rc1
Bb2 21. Nd4 {The point behind White's play.} Bxc1 22. Qxc1 Re8 23. Bh6 {
White simply intends Qc3 and has excellent play for the exchange, partly
because it's far from easy for Black to liberate his position.} f6 {Settling
for a grim defence.} 24. Qe3 {A brave choice, but if Black does nothing now
White will just go g4 followed by f4.} e5 {Black desperately tries to break
out.} 25. dxe6 Bxe6 {25...Nxe6? 26.Nxf5 gxf5 would be an extremely disgusting
structure for Black and surely lost.} 26. Qf3 Bf5 27. Qd5+ Be6 28. Qxd6 {
White has picked off a pawn, his diagonal-moving creatures still rule the
roost and he clearly has too much for the exchange.} *

