1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e6 {The choice of Nimzo-Indian and QGD aficionados. Black
players would like nothing more than 3 d4 and a transposition to their
favourite defence after 3...Bb4 or 3...d5. White should certainly avoid 3 g3
d5, but fortunately help is at hand in the shape of one of our favourite
advances.} 3. e4 {The Mikenas Attack, named after the Lithuanian GM Vladas
Mikenas. White aggressively conquers space in the centre and threatens e5.} Bb4
{The@move Black would play had we gone 3 d4, but it's simply not good here.
Alternatively: The complex, but fun old main line is 3...c5 4.e5 , as we'll
cover in Line 6A. A somewhat more solid option is the modern GM preference, 3..
.d5 , when 4 cxd5 exd5 5 e5 Ne4 6 Nf3 is trendy, but we'll see in Line 6B that
the immediate 4.e5 still packs a certain punch. In practice, 3...d6 isn't that
far behind 3...c5 in the popularity stakes, largely because it is seen quite
often at lower levels. Indeed, based on when your authors have given simuls,
the Mikenas continues to catch out plenty of black players at club level. Here
you might very well be happy with 4 d4 and a very pleasant space advantage,
but 4.g3 is also possible when 4...Be7 5.Bg2 leaves Black with a slightly
sub-optimal choice. If he simply pushes his e-pawn, he'll be a tempo down on
an Old Indian and those positions we considered in 2C. As such, 5...c5 is a
better choice when 6.Nge2 Nc6 7.O-O transposing to lines we considered last
chapter in 5A. 3...Nc6 ?! isn't so ridiculous and has even been tried with
success by Ivanchuk, albeit in a blitz game. That said, 4.d4
îîStartBracketîîif you prefer something more restrained then 4 Nf3 is a decent
choice, intending 4...d5 5 cxd5 exd5 6 e5 with a likely transposition to Line
6BîîEndBracketîî 4...Bb4 4...d5 is arguably less challenging and 5.cxd5 exd5 6.
e5 Ne4 7.Bb5 !? just a pleasant edge; White's space advantage should easily
outweigh the small hole on e4, with 7...Bb4 8.Nge2 O-O 9.O-O easy development,
after which 9...Nxc3 10.bxc3 Be7 11.Nf4 Bg5 12.Bd3 already left White eyeing
the black king and with a large advantage in Aronian-Wojtaszek, Dubai
îîStartBracketîîblitzîîEndBracketîî 2014 5.e5 ! îîStartBracketîîtaking up the
challenge, rather than allow Black to hit back with ...d5 or ...
e5îîEndBracketîî 5...Ne4 5...Ng8 6.Qg4 Kf8 7.Nf3 is also pretty pleasant for
White, who simply intends Be2 and 0-0, as well as a timely d5 or Ng5 and f4 6.
Qc2 d5 6...Qh4 is an idea sometimes seen in the English Defence, but here 7.
Be3 f5 8.exf6 Nxf6 9.Nf3 Qh5 10.Be2 leaves White with the better development,
and even 6...Nxc3 !? 7.bxc3 Be7 8.Nf3 b6 9.Qe4 !? Bb7 10.Qg4 shouldn't
equalise for Black, as he must now play a sub-optimal move to defend g7, not
permit 10...O-O ? 11.Bh6 7.Nf3 f6 8.Bd3 fxe5 9.dxe5 O-O didn't exactly
