1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e6 3. e4 d5 4. e5 {The old main line. White simply seizes
space and poses the question to the black knight without opening lines for the
bishop on c8.} d4 {This counterattack is by far Black's main move, although
the alternatives are sometimes seen, especially at non-GM level. 4...Ng8 ?!
One of the alternatives, but it is just a rather strange choice and after 5.d4
White has unsurprisingly scored very well: for example, 5...Ne7 Or 5...c6 6.
Nf3 h6 7.h4 !? h5 ? 8.Bg5 Be7 9.Bd3 Bxg5 10.Nxg5 Qe7 11.Rh3 which was all
rather one-way traffic in Marin-Knafo, Andorra 2000.6.Nf3 dxc4 7.Bxc4 Nd7 8.
O-O Nb6 9.Bb3 h6 10.a4 !? a6 11.a5 Nbd5 12.Bd2 with a handy development lead
and ideas of Qe2-e4, as well as a timely exchange on d5 in Chabanon-Gonzales,
Ibi 1996.} 5. exf6 dxc3 6. bxc3 Qxf6 {Invariably played, although Simon did
once face 6...gxf6 ?! 7.d4 c5 and now in Williams-Zigura, Budapest 1994, 8.Nf3
Bg7 9.Bd3 O-O 10.O-O would have maintained a pleasant edge, and if 10...Nc6 11.
d5 ! Ne7 12.Nh4 !? with the initiative.} 7. d4 {Naturally White is happy to
seize space and control the centre. He will now enjoy quick and easy
development with Nf3, Bd3 and O-O, and Black must be careful not to come under
a direct attack on the kingside.} c5 {Fractionally Black's most popular move
has been the alternative counter-strike 7... c5.} 8. Nf3 {This leaves Black at
a cross-roads: he can go for either 8...h6 or 8...cxd4.} cxd4 {This is, of
course, the move Black would like to play, but we don't have to allow him to
free his position with 9.cxd4 Bb4+.} 9. Bg5 {First winning a tempo before
recapturing on d4.} Qf5 {9...Qg6 ?! 10.Bd3 Qh5 11.cxd4 Bb4+ offers White a
pleasant choice between 12.Kf1!? and 12.Bd2 Bxd2+ 13.Qxd2 O-O 14.O-O Nc6 15.
Rfe1 and if Rd8 16.d5 ! which saw the 1. c4 legend breaking through in J.
Watson-Vinje Gulbrandsen, Gausdal 1981, in view of 16...exd5 ? 17.cxd5 Qxd5 18.
Re8+ ! Rxe8 19.Bxh7+ Kxh7 20.Qxd5} 10. cxd4 Nc6 11. a3 {A good reply,
preventing any check on b4. White can follow up with Bd3.} Qa5+ 12. Bd2 Qd8 13.
Bc3 Be7 14. d5 {already left Black under pressure in Tukmakov-Dobosz, Yerevan
1980.} *

